<TITLE> Matia brands BGMEA as land-grabber </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 26 (bdnews24.com)  Agriculture minister Matia Chowdhury has branded country's apparel exporters' association BGMEA as 'land-grabber' and a section of its leaders as 'educated criminals'. "BGMEA has erected a building in the very Hatirjheel area. Now they are advocating protection of environment Not all, those who commit crimes but suggest good things for others are educated criminals," she said. Speaking at the inauguration of a piloted floating house, Lift House, at House Building Research Institute at Mirpur in the city on Tuesday, the minister said the indiscriminate encroachment of open spaces has put water-logging in Dhaka city at an alarming point. "Hatirjheel was encroached. Now its land is being recovered." There are allegations that Bangladesh Garment Manufacturers and Exporters Association (BGMEA) has developed the building grabbing lands of Hatirjheel, where the city development authority Rajuk is implementing a taka 1,480 crore (14.8 billion) Hatirjheel-Begunbari integrated project. Housing and public works minister Abdul Mannan Khan in June last year said the project, aimed to preserve rainwater and eliminate water logging in the area and ease traffic gridlock by creating another east-west route in the city, would be completed on time leaving the BGMEA building intact. The incumbent Awami League-led government announced immediately after assuming office in early 2009 that illegal structures in Dhaka city would be dismantled and the rivers circling the city recovered from encroachers. Finance minister Abul Maal Abdul Muhith inaugurated the house, built by Canada's Waterloo University student Prithula Prasun. The sate minister for housing, speaking on the occasion, urged the real estate developers build houses for poor people. "You are not only for the rich and middle-income people. You have to come forward to build houses for the poor," he sai
